post_text:
Spice Adams graced RVLA with his presence today and spoke on education being powerful, how sports shaped his life, and how education as an adult catapulted him into starting his own Production Company. We honor and thank Anthony "Spice" Adams for taking the time to impart his wisdom and shared experiences with our Rainier Valley Leadership Academy community, and all the way from Chicago! Thank you for the laughs, honesty, and wisdom!

So who is up next?! We need speakers weekly, 1p-1:45p every Wednesday..

Every week we have a live Panther Talk with a Global Majority aka (Person of Color) Leader in our local and national community. We ask them to come in and get back to the roots of storytelling, an art many of our GM ancestors have used to share history and wisdom. Speakers discuss their upbringing, their career path, why education is important and how to navigate a world that has often cared for to little for such priceless gems. To sign up please go here and fill out the form: https://forms.gle/d3sacY2oXHdyjZeF6

If you are a Global Majority aka BIPOC Professional, please read on. If you are not GM or BIPOC please forward to others you think may be interested in speaking to our scholars.
Panther talks are opportunities for our Global Majority leaders to come and speak to our scholars in a storytelling format with a Q&A at the end. Story telling is an indigenous practice that has not been as highly regarded as it should be and was to many of our ancestors. This practice allows for scholars to see people who look like them in various career fields. We want to bring forward the excellence that is Global Majority people so our scholars recognize others are where they aspire to be and these are opportunities for them to begin their own stories. To sign up for to be speaker at a Panther Talk please fill out the form below. We will review your application and confirm your time slot. Panther Talks are 45 minutes, every Wednesday from 1p-1:45p. #RVLA #RVLASEA #antiracism #BLM #antiracisteducation #education

post_text:
While we celebrate Memorial Day, please also celebrate Africa Day!

Africa Day (formerly African Freedom Day and African Liberation Day) is the annual commemoration of the foundation of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) (now known as the African Union) on 25 May 1963. It is celebrated in various countries on the African continent, as well as around the world.

Sen. Rebecca Saldaña

post_text:
The current assigned lessons in Music Appreciation cover Modern Jazz. The end of each lesson recommends some listening examples and Mr. Berry would like to share one of his favorites.

The Black Saint and the Sinner Lady is an album released by legendary jazz bassist and composer Charles Mingus. The album consists of a single continuous composition - partially written as a ballet - divided into four tracks and six movements. Today, the album stands as one of the most acclaimed jazz records of the 20th century and has been called “one of the greatest achievements in orchestration by any composers in jazz history”.

Check it out here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zFA0FYQo0Gg

post_text:
Here is some insight to how one of our Scholar Ambassadors is during remote learning:

Hello, during this time I think we shouldn't be looking at the things like death polls and what has been getting worse, we should be looking at more positive things, like how many people have recovered. That's how I've kept going during this time. I get my work done by getting up early, have a good breakfast, and focusing a couple of hours of my day dedicated to getting my work done. Some tips I have for scholars is to give yourself a good motivation, like maybe if you finish a lesson you'll let yourself have a treat at the end, another tip I have is to make sure you get notes down that can help you in quizzes on APEX, and also not procrastinating, put your distracting devices away and focus on your work. Thank you.

-Misk Alqaysi

#TestimonialTuesdays #RVLA

ATTENTION SCHOLARS! A great activity you can do is to keep a journal over the next 5+ weeks. Handwritten, typed, in photographs or drawings....record events, day to day activities, fears and feelings. Make a video journal if that is what you prefer. Interview your parents, guardians, friends, family, let everyone around you be a part of this experience and history. You will be able to share this with your children and grandchildren, friends to be. Help yourself create a physical and primary source of your own HISTORY.

Check out these journal ideas: shorturl.at/gzDGW

post_text: Here is another great resource for families in our community
shared_text:
Chukundi Salisbury
March 12 at 8:25 PM ·

If you or anyone you know – at ANY age – needs groceries or meals at no charge, please come to Northwest Harvest’s SODO Community Market at 1915 4th Ave S in Seattle’s SODO neighborhood. You can pick up pre-bagged produce, prepared foods, and shelf-stable groceries right at the door – no need to enter the grocery area. All are welcome and no ID is required.

We will be available to families while local school districts develop solutions to make sure children are getting meals while schools across the region are closed due to health concerns relating to the COVID-19 virus.

SODO Community Market hours are Monday, 1:30 to 7:30 PM and Wednesdays & Fridays, 8:00AM to 2:00PM.

We plan on having a variety of healthy foods to distribute freely for everyone who comes.

PLEASE share this post to help ensure all those who need food during this time can get food.

https://buff.ly/3cU7FKO

post_text:
Inside RVLA: Collaboration and the ability to work in a group are all apart of an RVLA classroom and a key skill needed to be successful in college, leadership and life. Students have multiple opportunities to work with their fellow classmates and build skills around working in a group. While this may seem like a given skill it takes focus and the desire to have productive group time to work in a small group and have deep intellectual conversation.

Teachers work with students throughout the year in building skills around asking probing questions, cultivating the ability to listen to each other, modeling the task at hand and of course creating content that is fun and exciting. Building these skills in each student prepares them for college and the real world.

Parents are encouraged to assist in building this skill at home by creating projects with siblings with clear outcomes and asking follow up questions to their student.

If you're interested in checking out an RVLA classroom call us today to schedule your campus tour at 206-659-0956

Inside RVLA:
The winter enrichment session will span from January 14th-April 5th. Students will have the opportunity to participate in a wide array of enrichment activities for 45 minutes, 3 days per week.

Parents are encouraged to check in with their student to find out what clubs their students in. Your student could be learning a new song in choir, practicing a new hip hop dance team or drill team routine, learning all about budgeting and financing, exploring how to put a robot together in robotics or practicing their jab in boxing. You can explore the full list of club offerings at the link below based off of student feedback:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vTXsSZo9nnFtWEUjHgV5LYq9hfKhk-wVCv_DuD59hQLOzqyp98IlNZWEwXOsmDRW2pjRIDVotZrMWxO/pub

If you're an interested community member who wants to volunteer your time and bring your talents to RVLA reach out to our enrichment supervisor Ms Carter at dcarter@seattleymca.org

As we celebrate the legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. RVLA students are using visual representation of what peace looks like in art class. They are applying previously learned sculpture techniques to create a mosaic stepping stone. They are representing peace by creating a peace path that will become a permanent fixture at RVLA.

Join us in honoring the legacy of Dr. King.

"Peace is not merely a distant goal that we seek, but a means by which we arrive at that goal." Dr. King

post_text:
Inside RVLA:

This weeks spotlight is a focus on science. Each student receives a block period of science, which is an extended period of more than 80 minutes at least 3 times a week of science. Students have the opportunity to use an RVLA core value, exploration, to dive deeper into science content. Students explore through class discussions, hands on experiments and dissection labs.

Parents can help expand their students exploration of science by asking an end of the day probing question such as," What is one thing you hope to learn more about in science before the school year is over?"

Interested families can schedule an in school campus tour today to check out a science class by reaching out to inforvla@greendot.org for more information.

post_text:
Inside RVLA: We have a basketball team! This season is our first season playing against our fellow charter middle schools in the Seattle/Kent area.

Our basketball team is an enrichment club offering where students spend 2 days per week practicing and playing games in the month of January. Students are required to maintain academic excellence and our coaches are there to support them in creating academic and behavioral goals. You can see our student athletes in action by checking out our schedule and attending a game.

If anyone is interested in volunteering to support this season and future seasons you can volunteer to be a referee, a coach, a team manager or a league organizer. Email the RVLA enrichment supervisor at dcarter@seattleymca.org

Check out a few photos from our kick off game in December versus Summit Atlas.

post_text:
We believe it is our responsibility to foster a school environment where students and families feel safe and supported. To ensure this, we have not and will not collect information related to student and family immigration status. Our staff will protect our students’ privacy rights to the greatest extent of the law. For information and resources to address your concerns or questions about immigration policies, visit http://greendot.org/immigration/#daca
---
Creemos que es nuestra responsabilidad de promover un ambiente escolar donde los estudiantes y las familias se sientan apoyados y seguros. Para asegurar esto, no hemos recopilado ninguna información relacionada con el estatus migratorio de los estudiantes y sus familias. Nuestro personal protegerá los derechos de privacidad de nuestros estudiantes con la mayor medida de la ley. Para obtener información y recursos y responder a sus preguntas y preocupaciones sobre las pólizas de inmigración, visite a http://greendot.org/immigration/#daca
shared_text:
BLOG.GREENDOT.ORG
Statement by Green Dot CEO Marco Petruzzi on the Trump Administration Decision to Repeal DACA - Green Dot Public Schools Blog

Green Dot Public Schools
September 6, 2017 at 8:43 PM ·

As educators, we know firsthand that our students are children first, and deserve every opportunity to succeed rather than be held accountable for decisions they weren’t party to. Children under DACA’s protection know this country as their home, and in many cases, as their only home. Read the statement by Green Dot Public Schools' CEO, Marco Petruzzi, on the blog.
text:
We believe it is our responsibility to foster a school environment where students and families feel safe and supported. To ensure this, we have not and will not collect information related to student and family immigration status. Our staff will protect our students’ privacy rights to the greatest extent of the law. For information and resources to address your concerns or questions about immigration policies, visit http://greendot.org/immigration/#daca
---

Para asegurar esto, no hemos recopilado ninguna información relacionada con el estatus migratorio de los estudiantes y sus familias. Nuestro personal protegerá los derechos de privacidad de nuestros estudiantes con la mayor medida de la ley. Para obtener información y recursos y responder a sus preguntas y preocupaciones sobre las pólizas de inmigración, visite a http://greendot.org/immigration/#daca
